Arroyo toad is known in Sepse Creek nearby. Key characteristics that point to Arroyo rather than California toad: widely separated oblong paratoid glands with pale front, pale on sacral humps and middle of back and light V across head. It does have faint pale stripe down back which is often thought of indicative of California toad, but other iNaturalist pictures of Arroyo toad show some with light stipe. 
I donât have much direct experience with Arroyo toads, so if someone thinks this is a California toad instead please speak up.

description: On June 20, CDFW fish biologist Austin Sturkie and I conducted a nighttime arroyo toad survey along San Ysabel Creek.  Due to the 2022-2023 rain year (July 1 - June 30) being above normal, flow in the creek along the low gradient portions remained several inches deep on this date.  Seven adult male AT individuals (some vocalizing) were observed, with some having trouble maintaining their positions while perched in the current.  In addition to the ATs, one large bullfrog was detected by eyeshine approximately 2 meters from a male AT.  This was the first bullfrog I have observed along this seasonal/ephemeral portion of the creek in over a decade of conducting AT surveys at this site.  Suspecting that it was focused on an AT, it was hand captured, put down with by pith, and dissected on site.  Because the partially digested AT was not part of a USFWS permitted project, it could not be collected for a museum voucher.

tag_list: mixed species, larvae
description:
Survey conducted by CDFW fish biologist Austin Sturkie and I.  The accuracy is 150 meters to capture the linear distance up & down stream from central  point.  Multiple obs. all along drainage channel.  No adult ATs observed.  These observations were made in somewhat uncharacteristic locations at a fine scale in that they all occurred in a boulder strewn reach greater than the typical > 3% grade, and not in quiet channels of low-gradient sandy reaches.  The larvae all found in small residual puddles among boulders because that is the only place surface water remained after the late season stream flow dropped to mostly subsurface flow. 
All larvae observed were either P. hypochondriaca, P. cadaverina, or A. californicus.  Several fatty fat boreas metamorphs obs during this survey.  A. boreas tads were observed at this site 4 weeks ago when no AT tads were obs.

The seemingly low precision location metric is because the coordinates represent the midpoint of a stream reach where multiple obs were made. 
 All obs made along the creek channel mostly among a boulder(y) reach.  At least 5 individual AT metamorphs obs. Many P. cadaverina, a few A. boreas metamorphs also obs.
See companion record 174152330 for details of habitat characteristics.
